Theorem (fuerstenberg):
  for all v0, (if v0 is a class and for all v1, (v1 is an element of v0 iff (v1 is an object and for some v2, (v2 is an integer and it is wrong that (v2 is equal to 0) and v2 is prime and v1 is equal to ArSeq( 0 , v2 )))) then it is wrong that (v0 is finite))
Proof:
  S is a family of integer sets
  ~ \bigcup S is a class and for all v0, (v0 is an element of ~ \bigcup S iff (v0 is an object and (v0 is equal to 1 or v0 is equal to - 1)))
  Proof:
    for all v0, (if v0 is an integer then (v0 is an element of \bigcup S iff for some v1, (v1 is a divisor of v0 and v1 is prime)))
    Proof:
      n is an integer
      if for some v0, (v0 is a divisor of n and v0 is prime) then n is an element of \bigcup S
      Proof:
        for some v0, (v0 is a divisor of n and v0 is prime)
        p is a divisor of n and p is prime
        ArSeq( 0 , p ) is a set
        ArSeq( 0 , p ) is an element of S
        n is an element of ArSeq( 0 , p )
      Qed.
      if n is an element of \bigcup S then for some v0, (v0 is a divisor of n and v0 is prime)
      Proof:
        n is an element of \bigcup S
        r is an integer and it is wrong that (r is equal to 0) and r is prime and n is an element of ArSeq( 0 , r )
        r is a divisor of n and r is prime
      Qed.
    Qed.
  Qed.
  S is finite
  \bigcup S is closed and ~ \bigcup S is open
  p is an integer and it is wrong that (p is equal to 0) and ArSeq( 1 , p ) is a subclass of ~ \bigcup S
  for some v0, (v0 is an element of ArSeq( 1 , p ) and it is wrong that (v0 is equal to 1) and it is wrong that (v0 is equal to - 1))
  Proof:
    1 + p is an integer and 1 + - p is an integer
    1 + p is an element of ArSeq( 1 , p ) and 1 + - p is an element of ArSeq( 1 , p )
    Proof:
      1 + p = 1 (mod p ) and 1 + - p = 1 (mod p )
    Qed.
    it is wrong that (1 + p is equal to 1) and it is wrong that (1 + - p is equal to 1)
    it is wrong that (1 + p is equal to - 1) or it is wrong that (1 + - p is equal to - 1)
  Qed.
  falsity holds
Qed.

